In [94]:
# Total Amount vs Gender
sales_gender = df.groupby(['Gender'], as_index=False)['Amount'].sum().sort_values(by='Amount',ascending=False)
sns.barplot(x='Gender',y='Amount', data=sales_gender)
Out[94]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='Gender', ylabel='Amount'>

From above graphs we can observe that females buy more than males and even the purchasing power of females is higher than males.

State¶

In [99]:
# total Amount/Sales in from top 10 states
sales_state = df.groupby(['State'], as_index=False)['Amount'].sum().sort_values(by='Amount', ascending=False).head(10)
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(25,10)})
sns.barplot(data=sales_state, x='State',y='Amount')
Out[99]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='State', ylabel='Amount'>

From the above graphs we can observe that the total number of orders are highest in Uttar Pradesh, Maharashtra and Karnataka respectively while total sales are highest in the same sates too.

Conclusion¶

Married women from UP, Maharashtra and Karnataka working in IT, Healthcare and Aviation are more likely to buy products from Food, Clothing and Electronics Categories respectively.
